<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Speed Anagramming Techniques</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">2-letter words · Bingo</p>

    <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
      <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
      <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
      <span>7 min read</span>
    </div>

    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">The difference between a good Scrabble player and a great one often comes down to speed. Not clock management, but how quickly you look at seven tiles and see words hiding inside them. Speed anagramming is a trainable skill — these techniques will help you find words faster under pressure.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Technique 1 — Vowel-Consonant Separation</h2>

    <p>The first step with any rack is mentally splitting it into vowels and consonants. This simple reorganisation reveals patterns invisible when tiles sit in random order.</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Example</p>
      <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Random rack: <span class="text-white font-medium">T R A I N E S</span></p>
      <p class="text-base text-gray-200 mt-1">After separation: <span class="text-amber-400 font-medium">A I E</span> | <span class="text-cyan-400 font-medium">T R N S</span></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mt-2">3 vowels + 4 consonants = balanced rack with bingo potential. The consonant cluster TRNS suggests -TION or TRANS- patterns.</p>
    </div>

    <p>This works because English follows predictable vowel-consonant patterns. A balanced rack (3 vowels + 4 consonants) almost always contains multiple words. Heavy vowel racks (4+) signal words like IDEA, ARIA, or suffixes like -ATE.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Technique 2 — Prefix and Suffix Scanning</h2>

    <p>Before trying to see whole words, scan for common beginnings and endings. If you spot one, mentally set those tiles aside and focus on what remains.</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🏷️ High-Value Prefixes</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">UN- (2), RE- (2), OUT- (3), OVER- (4), MIS- (3), PRE- (3), DIS- (3), NON- (3), SUB- (3)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🏷️ High-Value Suffixes</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">-ING (3), -TION (4), -ER (2), -ED (2), -LY (2), -NESS (4), -MENT (4), -ABLE (4), -IST (3)</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">✅ Power Move</p>
      <p class="text-base text-gray-200">If you spot <span class="text-white font-medium">-ING</span> in your rack, you only need to anagram the remaining 4 tiles. Four tiles are far easier to work with than seven.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Technique 3 — Alphabetical Ordering</h2>

    <p>Tournament players rearrange their physical tiles into alphabetical order. This seems minor but has a powerful effect: your brain stops seeing "random" and starts recognising familiar letter sequences.</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Eliminates scanning cost:</span> You always know where each letter sits — no more hunting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Reveals digraphs:</span> Adjacent alphabetical letters often form pairs (ST, TH, DE).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Builds pattern memory:</span> AEIRST always looks the same — you start recognising SATIRE stems instantly.</p>
      </div>
